---
import BaseLayout from '../../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const fullServerPy = String.raw`from typing import Any

import httpx
from mcp.server.fastmcp import FastMCP

mcp = FastMCP("Weather API Assistant")

OPEN_METEO_API_URL = "https://api.open-meteo.com/v1/forecast"

CITY_LOCATIONS = {
    "Taipei": {
        "latitude": 25.0330,
        "longitude": 121.5654,
    },
    "Taichung": {
        "latitude": 24.1477,
        "longitude": 120.6736,
    },
    "Kaohsiung": {
        "latitude": 22.6273,
        "longitude": 120.3014,
    },
    "Tamsui": {
        "latitude": 25.1676,
        "longitude": 121.4458,
    },
}


@mcp.tool()
def hello() -> str:
    """Confirm the weather API MCP server is up."""
    return "Weather API MCP server is running."


@mcp.tool()
def list_supported_cities() -> str:
    """List the cities currently supported."""
    cities = ", ".join(CITY_LOCATIONS.keys())
    return f"Supported cities: {cities}"


@mcp.tool()
def get_current_weather(city: str) -> str:
    """Look up the current weather for a supported city."""
    city = city.strip()

    if city not in CITY_LOCATIONS:
        supported_cities = ", ".join(CITY_LOCATIONS.keys())
        return (
            f"\"{city}\" is not supported. "
            f"Try one of these: {supported_cities}"
        )

    location = CITY_LOCATIONS[city]

    params = {
        "latitude": location["latitude"],
        "longitude": location["longitude"],
        "current": "temperature_2m,wind_speed_10m",
        "timezone": "Asia/Taipei",
    }

    try:
        with httpx.Client(timeout=10.0) as client:
            response = client.get(OPEN_METEO_API_URL, params=params)
            response.raise_for_status()
            data: dict[str, Any] = response.json()
    except httpx.TimeoutException:
        return "Timed out while fetching the weather. Please try again."
    except httpx.HTTPStatusError as error:
        return f"Weather API returned an error. Status code: {error.response.status_code}"
    except httpx.RequestError:
        return "Couldn't reach the weather API. Please check your connection."

    current = data.get("current", {})

    temperature = current.get("temperature_2m")
    wind_speed = current.get("wind_speed_10m")
    update_time = current.get("time")

    if temperature is None or wind_speed is None:
        return "The weather API responded, but the temperature or wind fields are missing."

    return (
        f"Current weather for {city}:\n"
        f"- Updated: {update_time}\n"
        f"- Temperature: ~{temperature} °C\n"
        f"- Wind speed: ~{wind_speed} km/h\n\n"
        f"Note: this is live data from an external weather API. "
        f"Conditions may still vary by exact location and time."
    )


if __name__ == "__main__":
    mcp.run()
`;
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Tool Wrapping: Turning External Services into MCP Tools — AI Agent Puzzle"
  description="Wrap an external API into an MCP tool the AI can actually use. The AI shouldn't have to read the whole API doc — it just needs a tool name and an input. The MCP Server handles city validation, lat/lon conversion, the API call, and shaping the response. Walked through with the Open-Meteo public API."
  lang="en"
>
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container ai-agent-wrapping">
      <a class="back-link" href="/">&larr; Back to Home</a>

      <header class="detail-header">
        <h1 class="detail-title">Don't Make the AI Read the API: Build a Tool For It</h1>
        <p class="detail-subtitle">
          We already know an MCP Server can act as the bridge between AI and external data. The AI doesn't barge into the external service — it works through tools we've already designed inside our MCP Server. The job for this page is simple: <strong>wrap an external API into an MCP tool the AI can use</strong>.
        </p>
      </header>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Without wrapping, code has to handle URLs, parameters, response data, and error messages. With wrapping, we tidy those details up so the AI sees something simple, like:
      </p>

      <blockquote class="prompt-example">
        Look up the current weather for a given city.
      </blockquote>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        The AI doesn't have to understand the API doc or build URLs. <strong>It just needs to know: when weather is needed, call the <code>get_current_weather</code> tool.</strong>
      </p>

      <!-- Section: API vs MCP Tool -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">The Short Version: API Is Raw Material, MCP Tool Is for the AI</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Separating the two:
      </p>

      <ul class="role-list">
        <li class="role-item">
          <span class="role-item__label">API</span>
          <span class="role-item__desc">The entry point the external service originally exposes</span>
        </li>
        <li class="role-item">
          <span class="role-item__label">MCP Tool</span>
          <span class="role-item__desc">The packaged version we shape for the AI</span>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        For example, an external weather API might want all of these inputs:
      </p>

      <ul class="check-list">
        <li>Latitude</li>
        <li>Longitude</li>
        <li>Which weather fields to fetch</li>
        <li>Response format</li>
        <li>Timezone</li>
      </ul>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        That's a lot for a beginner — and not necessarily the safest or most stable thing to expose to the AI. So we wrap it as a single MCP tool:
      </p>

      <div class="tool-box">
        <p class="tool-box__label">MCP Tool</p>
        <p class="tool-box__name"><code>get_current_weather(city)</code></p>
        <p class="tool-box__desc">The AI just supplies a city name; the MCP Server handles the rest</p>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">When the AI passes a city name, the MCP Server takes over:</p>

      <div class="flow-card flow-card--tall">
        <div class="flow-step">Validate the city name</div>
        <div class="flow-arrow">↓</div>
        <div class="flow-step">Look up latitude / longitude</div>
        <div class="flow-arrow">↓</div>
        <div class="flow-step flow-step--accent">Call the external weather API</div>
        <div class="flow-arrow">↓</div>
        <div class="flow-step">Shape the response</div>
        <div class="flow-arrow">↓</div>
        <div class="flow-step">Return a clean, readable result</div>
      </div>

      <div class="highlight-card">
        <p class="highlight-text">
          That's the heart of "wrap an API as an MCP tool":<br/>
          don't pass the API through raw — <strong>shape it into a tool that's easy for the AI and inspectable for humans</strong>.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Section: Use no-key API -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">Practice First With a No-Key API</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        We'll demo with <strong>Open-Meteo</strong>, a public weather API that doesn't require an API key. Open-Meteo's documentation notes that its API is free for non-commercial use and needs no key.
      </p>

      <div class="callout-card">
        <p class="callout-text">
          The win: we don't get stuck on <strong>account signup, key application, or pasting the wrong key</strong> on day one. We can focus on "how does an API become a tool" first.
        </p>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Once that flow is clear, switching to a key-protected service is one extra step — <strong>read the API key from an environment variable</strong>. We covered that on the previous page, so this page focuses on tool wrapping.
      </p>

      <!-- Section: Design tool first -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">Design the Tool First, Don't Rush to Code</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        First-time MCP tool authors often jump straight into <code>server.py</code>. Better:
      </p>

      <div class="highlight-card">
        <p class="highlight-text">
          <strong>Decide first how the AI is supposed to use this tool.</strong>
        </p>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">The tool we're designing here:</p>

      <div class="tool-box">
        <p class="tool-box__label">This page's tool</p>
        <p class="tool-box__name"><code>get_current_weather</code></p>
        <p class="tool-box__desc">Look up the current weather for a given city</p>
      </div>

      <h3 class="sub-heading">Input</h3>
      <ul class="check-list">
        <li><code>city</code>: the city name</li>
      </ul>

      <h3 class="sub-heading">What it returns</h3>
      <ul class="check-list">
        <li>City</li>
        <li>Update time</li>
        <li>Current temperature</li>
        <li>Current wind speed</li>
        <li>A short reminder note</li>
      </ul>

      <h3 class="sub-heading">What it does NOT do</h3>
      <ul class="cross-list">
        <li>Doesn't look up <strong>student personal data</strong></li>
        <li>Doesn't <strong>write</strong> data</li>
        <li>Doesn't <strong>delete</strong> data</li>
        <li>Doesn't let the AI pass <strong>arbitrary API URLs</strong></li>
        <li>Doesn't let the AI choose <strong>which external site to hit</strong></li>
      </ul>

      <div class="highlight-card">
        <p class="highlight-text">
          We're not building a "look-up-anything" mega-tool —<br/>
          <strong>just a small "look-up-weather-for-this-city" tool.</strong>
        </p>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Small tools are <strong>easier to teach, easier to test, and safer</strong>.
      </p>

      <!-- ============ Part 2: Hands-on ============ -->
      <div class="part-divider">
        <span class="part-label">PART 2</span>
        <span class="part-text">Hands-on</span>
      </div>

      <!-- STEP 1 -->
      <div class="case-header">
        <p class="case-label">STEP 1</p>
        <h2 class="case-title">Create the Project Folder</h2>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Create a fresh project folder, like:
      </p>

      <pre class="code-block code-block--tree" is:raw><code>my-weather-mcp-server/
├─ server.py
└─ .gemini/
   └─ settings.json</code></pre>

      <ul class="check-list">
        <li><code>server.py</code> is our MCP Server program</li>
        <li><code>.gemini/settings.json</code> tells Gemini CLI <strong>how to launch the MCP Server</strong></li>
      </ul>

      <div class="callout-card">
        <p class="callout-text">
          <strong>No .env yet</strong> — this weather API doesn't require a key. If we later switch to a key-protected service, that's when .env and .gitignore get added back in.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- STEP 2 -->
      <div class="case-header">
        <p class="case-label">STEP 2</p>
        <h2 class="case-title">Install the Packages</h2>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        If you've already used uv, run this from the project folder:
      </p>

      <pre class="code-block" is:raw><code class="lang-shell">uv init
uv add "mcp[cli]" httpx</code></pre>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        We add one extra package: <code>httpx</code>. <strong>httpx is a common Python library for making HTTP requests</strong> — basically, it's how our Python program calls external APIs. The flow now becomes:
      </p>

      <div class="flow-card flow-card--tall">
        <div class="flow-step">Gemini CLI</div>
        <div class="flow-arrow">↓</div>
        <div class="flow-step flow-step--accent">MCP Tool</div>
        <div class="flow-arrow">↓</div>
        <div class="flow-step">Python uses httpx to call the weather API</div>
        <div class="flow-arrow">↓</div>
        <div class="flow-step">API returns data</div>
        <div class="flow-arrow">↓</div>
        <div class="flow-step flow-step--accent">MCP Tool shapes it and hands it back to Gemini</div>
      </div>

      <!-- STEP 3 -->
      <div class="case-header">
        <p class="case-label">STEP 3</p>
        <h2 class="case-title">Write a Weather-Capable MCP Server</h2>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Open <code>server.py</code> and drop in the following code:
      </p>

      <details class="details-card details-card--code">
        <summary class="details-card__summary">
          <span class="details-card__icon" aria-hidden="true">▸</span>
          <span class="details-card__title">Full server.py</span>
          <span class="details-card__hint">Click to expand the code</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="details-card__body details-card__body--flush">
          <pre class="code-block code-block--in-details"><code class="lang-python">{fullServerPy}</code></pre>
        </div>
      </details>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        That's a basic API-style MCP Server. It exposes three tools:
      </p>

      <ul class="check-list">
        <li><code>hello</code> — <strong>confirms the server started</strong></li>
        <li><code>list_supported_cities</code> — <strong>lists the cities supported right now</strong></li>
        <li><code>get_current_weather</code> — the one that <strong>actually calls the external API</strong></li>
      </ul>

      <div class="callout-card">
        <p class="callout-text">
          The MCP Python SDK lets you build a server with <code>FastMCP</code>, and uses Python functions, type hints, and docstrings to derive tool definitions. That's why our code uses <code>@mcp.tool()</code> to turn an ordinary function into an MCP tool.
        </p>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Want to dig into the internals? Expand the three sections below:
      </p>

      <details class="details-card">
        <summary class="details-card__summary">
          <span class="details-card__icon" aria-hidden="true">▸</span>
          <span class="details-card__title"> What this code is doing</span>
          <span class="details-card__hint">Click to expand</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="details-card__body">
          <p class="detail-paragraph">First, this line:</p>
          <pre class="code-block" is:raw><code class="lang-python">mcp = FastMCP("Weather API Assistant")</code></pre>
          <p class="detail-paragraph">
            We're creating an MCP Server named <strong>Weather API Assistant</strong>. The name signals to the system: "this server is a weather API assistant."
          </p>

          <p class="detail-paragraph">Then this:</p>
          <pre class="code-block" is:raw><code class="lang-python">CITY_LOCATIONS = {
    "Taipei": {
        "latitude": 25.0330,
        "longitude": 121.5654,
    },
    ...
}</code></pre>
          <p class="detail-paragraph">
            We <strong>hard-code the supported cities</strong>. Why not let the AI pass any city? <strong>Because we're beginners</strong>. Starting with a smaller scope is easier to observe and less prone to surprises.
          </p>

          <p class="detail-paragraph">If a student types "Taipei," the program already knows the lat/lon. If a student types "Mars," the program responds:</p>
          <blockquote class="prompt-example">
            "Mars" is not supported.
          </blockquote>

          <div class="callout-card">
            <p class="callout-text">
              That's <strong>input restriction</strong> — not to make life hard, but to <strong>make the tool more stable</strong>.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="details-card">
        <summary class="details-card__summary">
          <span class="details-card__icon" aria-hidden="true">▸</span>
          <span class="details-card__title"> Where the API actually gets called</span>
          <span class="details-card__hint">Click to expand</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="details-card__body">
          <p class="detail-paragraph">
            The most important section of this tool:
          </p>
          <pre class="code-block" is:raw><code class="lang-python">with httpx.Client(timeout=10.0) as client:
    response = client.get(OPEN_METEO_API_URL, params=params)
    response.raise_for_status()
    data: dict[str, Any] = response.json()</code></pre>

          <p class="detail-paragraph">
            Picture it as: <strong>Python knocking on the external API's door</strong>.
          </p>

          <ul class="check-list">
            <li><code>client.get(...)</code> <strong>sends the request</strong></li>
            <li><code>params=params</code> <strong>passes the query parameters</strong></li>
            <li><code>response.raise_for_status()</code> <strong>checks for an error response</strong></li>
            <li><code>response.json()</code> <strong>turns the API's JSON into a Python-friendly structure</strong></li>
          </ul>

          <div class="highlight-card">
            <p class="highlight-text">
              API responses usually aren't pretty articles —<br/>
              <strong>they're more like a packet of data.</strong>
            </p>
          </div>

          <p class="detail-paragraph">
            So the MCP tool's job is <strong>to shape that packet first, then hand it to the AI</strong>.
          </p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="details-card">
        <summary class="details-card__summary">
          <span class="details-card__icon" aria-hidden="true">▸</span>
          <span class="details-card__title"> Why not dump the whole API response into the AI</span>
          <span class="details-card__hint">Click to expand</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="details-card__body">
          <p class="detail-paragraph">
            One question: if the API returns a lot of data, why not just hand it all to the AI? <strong>Not necessarily a good idea</strong>. A few problems:
          </p>

          <ul class="cross-list">
            <li>The data is <strong>too long</strong></li>
            <li>The AI <strong>misses what matters</strong></li>
            <li><strong>Users can't read it</strong></li>
            <li>Fields you don't need <strong>get exposed anyway</strong></li>
            <li>Debugging gets <strong>harder to trace</strong></li>
          </ul>

          <p class="detail-paragraph">
            So inside the tool, we <strong>pick only the fields this task needs</strong>:
          </p>

          <pre class="code-block" is:raw><code class="lang-python">temperature = current.get("temperature_2m")
wind_speed = current.get("wind_speed_10m")
update_time = current.get("time")</code></pre>

          <p class="detail-paragraph">Then format them into something readable:</p>

          <pre class="code-block" is:raw><code class="lang-python">return (
    f"Current weather for {city}:\n"
    f"- Updated: {update_time}\n"
    f"- Temperature: ~{temperature} °C\n"
    f"- Wind speed: ~{wind_speed} km/h\n\n"
    f"Note: this is live data from an external weather API. "
    f"Conditions may still vary by exact location and time."
)</code></pre>

          <div class="highlight-card">
            <p class="highlight-text">
              That's a key MCP tool responsibility:<br/>
              <strong>not just shuffling API data, but pre-shaping it into something both AI and humans can read.</strong>
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </details>

      <!-- STEP 4 -->
      <div class="case-header">
        <p class="case-label">STEP 4</p>
        <h2 class="case-title">Connect the MCP Server to Gemini CLI</h2>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Inside the project, your <code>.gemini/settings.json</code> can look like:
      </p>

      <pre class="code-block" is:raw><code class="lang-json">{
  "mcpServers": {
    "weather-api": {
      "command": "uv",
      "args": ["run", "python", "server.py"],
      "cwd": "Replace with the full path to your project folder",
      "timeout": 30000,
      "trust": false,
      "includeTools": [
        "hello",
        "list_supported_cities",
        "get_current_weather"
      ]
    }
  }
}</code></pre>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Remember to set <code>cwd</code> to your actual project folder. We're keeping <code>includeTools</code> here too. The reason:
      </p>

      <div class="highlight-card">
        <p class="highlight-text">
          Even if you wrote the MCP Server yourself,<br/>
          <strong>don't get into the habit of "expose everything."</strong>
        </p>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Right now we only need three tools, so only three are exposed.
      </p>

      <!-- STEP 5 -->
      <div class="case-header">
        <p class="case-label">STEP 5</p>
        <h2 class="case-title">Verify the Tool Works</h2>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Launch Gemini CLI from VS Code's integrated terminal:
      </p>

      <pre class="code-block" is:raw><code class="lang-shell">gemini</code></pre>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">Inside Gemini CLI, type:</p>

      <pre class="code-block" is:raw><code class="lang-shell">/mcp list</code></pre>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        If you see <code>weather-api</code> connected, Gemini CLI found the MCP Server. Try:
      </p>

      <blockquote class="prompt-example">
        Please call the hello tool from weather-api.
      </blockquote>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">If it replies "Weather API MCP server is running.", that's the first checkpoint passed. Then try:</p>

      <blockquote class="prompt-example">
        Please list the cities I can look up.
      </blockquote>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">And:</p>

      <blockquote class="prompt-example">
        Please look up the current weather in Taipei and present it in a way that's easy for college students to read.
      </blockquote>

      <div class="highlight-card">
        <p class="highlight-text">
          At this point the AI <strong>isn't answering out of thin air</strong>.<br/>
          It's actually <strong>going through an MCP tool to query an external API</strong>.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- ============ Part 3: Safety + Advanced ============ -->

      <!-- Section: Three layers of protection -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">This Tool Quietly Has Three Layers of Protection</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        It looks like a weather lookup, but it actually demonstrates an important <strong>safety mindset</strong>.
      </p>

      <ul class="role-list">
        <li class="role-item">
          <span class="role-item__label">Layer 1</span>
          <span class="role-item__desc"><strong>Supports a fixed list of cities only.</strong> The AI can't pass arbitrary locations or modify the API query scope.</span>
        </li>
        <li class="role-item">
          <span class="role-item__label">Layer 2</span>
          <span class="role-item__desc"><strong>Returns only the current weather.</strong> The tool isn't a "weather Swiss-army knife" — it does one thing.</span>
        </li>
        <li class="role-item">
          <span class="role-item__label">Layer 3</span>
          <span class="role-item__desc"><strong>Returns only the fields we need.</strong> The full API response never reaches the AI; the tool selects and formats first.</span>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Together, these three things are the <strong>design mindset</strong> this MCP tool tries to convey:
      </p>

      <ul class="check-list">
        <li>A bit <strong>smaller</strong> in scope</li>
        <li>A bit <strong>clearer</strong> in range</li>
        <li>A bit <strong>cleaner</strong> in output</li>
      </ul>

      <!-- Section: API Key version -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">If the API Later Needs an API Key, How to Adjust</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Our API doesn't need a key. But many external services do. If you switch to a key-protected API, <strong>don't write</strong>:
      </p>

      <pre class="code-block code-block--bad" is:raw><code class="lang-python">api_key = "your-real-api-key"</code></pre>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        That hard-codes the key in the source — <strong>not safe</strong>. The better way:
      </p>

      <pre class="code-block" is:raw><code class="lang-python">import os

api_key = os.getenv("WEATHER_API_KEY")

if not api_key:
    return "WEATHER_API_KEY not found. Please set the environment variable first."</code></pre>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        If the API expects the key in a header:
      </p>

      <pre class="code-block" is:raw><code class="lang-python">headers = {
    "Authorization": f"Bearer {api_key}"
}</code></pre>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">And pass it when calling the API:</p>

      <pre class="code-block" is:raw><code class="lang-python">response = client.get(API_URL, params=params, headers=headers)</code></pre>

      <div class="callout-card">
        <p class="callout-text">
          Don't rush to implement this yet. The single thing to remember: <strong>API keys are keys — don't hard-code them</strong>. Full setup is on the previous page: "<a href="/learning/ai-agent/api-server/keys">API Keys & Environment Variables</a>".
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Section: Common errors -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">Common Errors</h2>

      <details class="details-card">
        <summary class="details-card__summary">
          <span class="details-card__icon" aria-hidden="true">▸</span>
          <span class="details-card__title">1. Gemini can't find the MCP Server</span>
          <span class="details-card__hint">Click for the checklist</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="details-card__body">
          <p class="detail-paragraph">
            If <code>weather-api</code> doesn't show up under <code>/mcp list</code>, check:
          </p>
          <ul class="check-list">
            <li>Is <code>settings.json</code> inside the <code>.gemini</code> folder?</li>
            <li>Is <code>cwd</code> set to the <strong>correct path</strong>?</li>
            <li>Is the <code>server.py</code> filename spelled correctly?</li>
            <li>Did <code>uv</code> <strong>install successfully</strong>?</li>
          </ul>

          <p class="detail-paragraph">Quick test in the terminal:</p>
          <pre class="code-block" is:raw><code class="lang-shell">uv run python server.py</code></pre>

          <div class="callout-card">
            <p class="callout-text">
              If even that fails, <strong>the issue is in Python or package installation, not Gemini CLI</strong>.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="details-card">
        <summary class="details-card__summary">
          <span class="details-card__icon" aria-hidden="true">▸</span>
          <span class="details-card__title">2. httpx not found</span>
          <span class="details-card__hint">Click for the checklist</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="details-card__body">
          <p class="detail-paragraph">If you see something like:</p>
          <pre class="code-block" is:raw><code class="lang-shell">ModuleNotFoundError: No module named 'httpx'</code></pre>
          <p class="detail-paragraph">
            <code>httpx</code> isn't installed yet. From the project folder:
          </p>
          <pre class="code-block" is:raw><code class="lang-shell">uv add httpx</code></pre>
          <p class="detail-paragraph">
            Then <strong>relaunch Gemini CLI</strong>.
          </p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="details-card">
        <summary class="details-card__summary">
          <span class="details-card__icon" aria-hidden="true">▸</span>
          <span class="details-card__title">3. The API takes too long to respond</span>
          <span class="details-card__hint">Click for the checklist</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="details-card__body">
          <p class="detail-paragraph">There's this line in the program:</p>
          <pre class="code-block" is:raw><code class="lang-python">with httpx.Client(timeout=10.0) as client:</code></pre>
          <p class="detail-paragraph">
            That means <strong>wait at most 10 seconds</strong>. If the external API or the network is slow, you'll see:
          </p>
          <blockquote class="prompt-example">
            Timed out while fetching the weather. Please try again.
          </blockquote>
          <p class="detail-paragraph">
            This kind of error <strong>doesn't necessarily mean buggy code</strong>. Sometimes the network or the API is just temporarily flaky.
          </p>

          <div class="callout-card">
            <p class="callout-text">
